# language.p0t — LANGUAGE-BEHAVIOUR MATRIX (gen346).
#
# Verifies reply language across (environment language) x (prompt language). The
# environment is piloted with !set PARROT0_LANG + !reset; the prompt is a clear
# English greeting ("hello"), a clear Italian greeting ("buongiorno"), and an
# AMBIGUOUS one ("ciao") whose language the token alone cannot settle.
#
# NB "ciao" is placed FIRST in each block so it lands at turn 1 (a greeting): the
# same token late in a conversation is a farewell (discourse position), which is a
# DIFFERENT axis than language and would otherwise confound this matrix.
#
# DESIRED behaviour asserted here:
#   - a CLEAR prompt is answered in the prompt's own language (per-turn detection);
#   - an AMBIGUOUS prompt defers to the ENVIRONMENT language (the seed).
# Failing cells document where the engine diverges (today: the environment seed is
# ignored, so "ciao" is answered in Italian regardless of PARROT0_LANG).

# ============================ ENVIRONMENT = ENGLISH ============================
[mock env-english]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test en-env / ambiguous ciao -> environment english]
> ciao
< Hi there!

[test en-env / clear-english hello]
> hello
< Hi there!

[test en-env / clear-italian buongiorno]
> buongiorno
< Ciao!

# ============================ ENVIRONMENT = ITALIAN ============================
[mock env-italian]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=it
!reset

[test it-env / ambiguous ciao -> environment italian]
> ciao
< Ciao!

[test it-env / clear-english hello]
> hello
< Hi there!

[test it-env / clear-italian buongiorno]
> buongiorno
< Ciao!